# Zod v4 API Conventions

This project uses **Zod v4**. Do not use Zod v3 API patterns. The two versions have significant API differences that must not be mixed.

---

## String format validators

In Zod v4, string format validators were split into two categories:

1. **Top-level primitives** — standalone schema types, no longer chained on `z.string()`.
2. **`z.iso.*` namespace** — ISO 8601 date/time formats.

### UUID

```ts
// ❌ Zod v3 — forbidden
z.string().uuid()

// ✅ Zod v4
z.uuid()
```

### ISO 8601 datetime

```ts
// ❌ Zod v3 — forbidden
z.string().datetime()

// ✅ Zod v4
z.iso.datetime()
```

### ISO 8601 date

```ts
// ❌ Zod v3 — forbidden
z.string().date()

// ✅ Zod v4
z.iso.date()
```

### ISO 8601 time

```ts
// ❌ Zod v3 — forbidden
z.string().time()

// ✅ Zod v4
z.iso.time()
```

### Email

```ts
// ❌ Zod v3 — forbidden
z.string().email()

// ✅ Zod v4
z.email()
```

### URL

```ts
// ❌ Zod v3 — forbidden
z.string().url()

// ✅ Zod v4
z.url()
```

---

## General rule

> If you are chaining a format specifier (uuid, email, url, datetime, date, time) on `z.string()`, it is a Zod v3 pattern and must be replaced with the Zod v4 equivalent.

Plain `z.string()` without a format specifier remains valid for unformatted strings.
